1. Problem Statement¶

Create a machine learning model which predicts the price of Diamond using a dataset containing multiple values along with its price.¶

2. Data Collection¶

The Dataset was downloaded from kaggle.com

link : https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/amirhosseinmirzaie/diamonds-price-dataset¶

3. Importing and understanding the dataset¶

This dataset named "diamonds.csv" consists of 9 features, 1 label and 50,000 entries(rows).¶

Features :-¶

  • carat : weight of diamond in carat
  • cut : diamond cutting quality
  • color : diamond color
  • clarity : measure of diamond clarity
  • depth : percentage depth = z / mean(x,y)
  • table : The width of the widest point at the top of the diamond
  • x : diamond length in mm
  • y : diamond width in mm
  • z : diamond depth/height in mm

Label :-¶

  • price : price of the diamond (target variable)
In [3]:
a["cut"].unique()
Out[3]:
array(['Ideal', 'Premium', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Fair'], dtype=object)

These are different values of cutting quality of diamond

In [4]:
a["color"].unique()
Out[4]:
array(['E', 'I', 'J', 'H', 'F', 'G', 'D'], dtype=object)

These are different values of color of diamond, sequence goes as follows

  • D : Colorless (Best in class)
  • E : Colorless
  • F : Colorless
  • G : Near Colorless
  • H : Near Colorless
  • I : Near Colorless Slightly Tinted
  • J : Near Colorless Slightly Tinted

</b>

In [5]:
a["clarity"].unique()
Out[5]:
array(['SI2', 'SI1', 'VS1', 'VS2', 'VVS2', 'VVS1', 'I1', 'IF'],
      dtype=object)

The different values of clarity of diamond are as following (from best to worst order)

  • IF : Internally Flawless
  • VVS1 : Very Very Slightly Included Grade 1
  • VVS2 : Very Very Slightly Included Grade 2
  • VS1 : Very Slightly Included Grade 1
  • VS2 : Very Slightly Included Grade 2
  • SI1 : Slightly Included Grade 1
  • SI2 : Slightly Included Grade 2
  • I1 : Included Grade 1

included stands for impurity

</b>

De-noising¶

x, y and z are lengths so these columns can not have negative values or value = 0.
Negative values for these columns are most likely to be present because of human error.

In [10]:
noise_indexes = a[((a["x"] <= 0) | (a["y"] <= 0) | (a["z"] <= 0))].index
print(noise_indexes)
a = a.drop(noise_indexes)
print(a.shape)

Int64Index([ 2046,  4422,  5038,  9370, 10310, 11038, 12568, 14731, 22598,
            22721, 24222, 24336, 25439, 25509, 25726, 45910, 47724],
           dtype='int64')
(49857, 10)

Depth is the percentage depth and is dependent on x,y and z as :
depth = z / mean(x,y)
out of which neither numerator nor denominator could be negative.
So depth can't be negative too.

In [11]:
a[a["depth"]<=0]
Out[11]:
carat cut color clarity depth table price x y z

depth column dont have any negative values or 0.

Encoding the Categorical Data¶

Encoding is needed for "cut", "color" and "clarity" columns for converting categorical data into machine readable data.

Label Encoding¶

In [22]:
data = a
In [23]:
cut_mapping = {
    "Fair" : 0,
    "Good" : 1,
    "Very Good" : 2,
    "Premium" : 3,
    "Ideal" : 4,
}

color_mapping = {
    "J" : 0,
    "I" : 1,
    "H" : 2,
    "G" : 3,
    "F" : 4,
    "E" : 5,
    "D" : 6,
}

clarity_mapping = {
    "I1" : 0,
    "SI2" : 1,
    "SI1" : 2,
    "VS2" : 3,
    "VS1" : 4,
    "VVS2" : 5,
    "VVS1" : 6,
    "IF" : 7,
}

label_encoder = LabelEncoder()

# Encode the categorical column using the mapping dictionary
data['cut'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data['cut'].map(cut_mapping))

data['color'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data['color'].map(color_mapping))

data['clarity'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data['clarity'].map(clarity_mapping))

data

5. Splitting the data¶

We cant use whole data for train the model, we also need some part of it in order to test the accuracy of the trained model. so splitting is needed. It is preferred to split data in 70:30 ratio for training and testing purpose respectively.¶

In [24]:
X = data.drop(["price"],axis=1).values
Y = data['price'].values
In [25]:
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size = 0.3, random_state =0)

Polynomial Regression with degree = 2 seems to give accurate values for smaller values, but as values increases error also increases. It works far better than linear regression, But it also sometimes predicts -ve prices, which is impossible. And as the values increases the predicted values scatters more and more.
Here R2 score is 0.9643562795503912 which is much better than that of linear regression, other than that its Root-Mean Square Error = 751.6138321413683 and Mean Absolute Error = 447.41703992474095 , which are much lesser than those of Linear regression

Linear regression doesn't give good results.
Polynomial regression and Decision tree gives nearly equal results but decision tree wins because its Mean Absolute Error is less
KNN algorithm is better than Linear regression but not equivalent to polynomial regression
Random forest gives best results in all aspects
so the sequence goes as follows :

  • Linear regression
  • K-Nearest Neighbour
  • Polynomial Regression
  • Decision Tree
  • random Forest

8. Conclusion¶

  • ### De-noising data (specially removing outliers) is very important step in data preprocessing, it exponentially reduces possibility of overfitting.

  • ### While working on any dataset, we cannot conclude anything after applying single algorithm, we need to apply many different algorithms and evaluate them one by one, it is a hit and trial process to obtain best result.

  • ### By observing the graph of predictions of linear regression, we can clearly say that, in this dataset label wasn't linearly dependent on features.

  • ### R2 score isnt enough to evaluate correctness of any model, its is must to check other parameters too like Root Mean Square Error and Mean Absolute error. Plotting the scatter plot visualizes various things and can help in evaluation by visualizing how scaterred or how dense the data is.

  • ### For this Dataset, Random Forest worked best with R2 score of 0.98125, it seems like there was issue of overfitting in other algorithms which was resolved by Random Forest, resulting in higher accuracy( R2 score) and lower errors(Root Mean Square Error and Mean Absolute Error) as compared to other algorithms.
